{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":101428,"duration_api_ms":150207,"num_turns":9,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"21405f9a-0345-4d27-9696-7a6b06df35ac","total_cost_usd":0.5025814,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":29146,"cache_read_input_tokens":186307,"output_tokens":1937,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":29146,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":182,"outputTokens":8994,"cacheReadInputTokens":745409,"cacheCreationInputTokens":47290,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.17880539999999998,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000},"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":7,"outputTokens":1937,"cacheReadInputTokens":186307,"cacheCreationInputTokens":29146,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.323776,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Reviewed both amendments against the codebase. Amendment fr-3-7544fce3 (deny_unknown_fields) identifies a real defense-in-depth gap but the trade-off with forward-compatibility is significant and the CI round-trip tests already cover the critical failure mode. Amendment fr-3-0471f60c (plan_hash snapshot backfill for replay) proposes changing deliberately designed and extensively tested behavior that exists for good safety reasons.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-3-7544fce3","decision":"accept","rationale":"The observation is technically correct: without #[serde(deny_unknown_fields)], production deserialization silently drops unknown fields, which is the same struct-drift failure mode the round-trip tests were introduced to prevent. The round-trip tests in CI (lines 3759-3800 of fs.rs) catch this during development, but adding deny_unknown_fields would catch it at runtime too. The forward-compatibility concern is real — if a newer version writes journal entries with new fields, an older binary with deny_unknown_fields would fail to parse them. However, the amendment explicitly acknowledges this and proposes test-only gating as a mitigation, which is a pragmatic middle ground. Even without the production attribute, a test-only assertion (e.g., deserializing with a deny_unknown_fields wrapper in tests) would strengthen the safety net at zero runtime cost. The suggestion is sound defense-in-depth with a clear implementation path."},{"amendment_id":"fr-3-0471f60c","decision":"reject","rationale":"This behavior is intentional and well-defended by design. I verified: (1) Two explicit code comments at fs.rs lines 2914-2918 and 3244-3248 explain that persist_plan() can advance snapshot.plan_hash after an attempt starts, making retroactive stamping unsafe. (2) Three dedicated tests exist in service.rs and pass: legacy_open_row_without_plan_hash_not_mislabeled_after_plan_evolution (line 5126) verifies that a legacy running row with plan_hash=None is NOT stamped after plan evolution, even through both replay and finalization; terminal_replay_legacy_row_without_plan_hash_stays_unset (line 5229) verifies that terminal replay with plan_hash=None does NOT stamp snapshot hash; terminal_replay_after_plan_evolution_succeeds (line 4846) verifies that replay works correctly when plans evolve. The amendment's proposed 'safe case' (snapshot unchanged since attempt start) would require tracking the temporal relationship between plan persistence and attempt creation — significant complexity for marginal benefit. The current design correctly errs toward not mislabeling, which is the safer default for lineage integrity."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"008548fc-1a45-4693-8dd3-3692e30de838"}
